  <text>
    <body>
      <p><persName ref="#ehri_et_wowsi_lila">Ela Wowsi</persName> Testimony (doc. 301/81)</p>

      <p>Original, manuscript, 4 pages, 210 x 295 mm, Polish language</p>

      <p>The experiences of a Jewish <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825" type="subject">woman</term>
        from <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/458258/republic-of-latvia.html"
          >Latvia</placeName> in the <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-567" type="subject">camps</term>
        in <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/456172/riga.html">Riga</placeName>, <placeName
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-857" type="camp"
          >Stutthof</placeName> and <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/7532549/torun.html"
          >Toruń</placeName></p>

      <p><persName ref="#ehri_et_wowsi_lila">Ela Wowsi</persName>, born in <date when="1898"
          >1898</date> in Subala in <placeName
          ref="http://www.geonames.org/458258/republic-of-latvia.html">Latvia</placeName>, lived in
          <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/460414/daugavpils.html">Dyneburg</placeName>,
        pharmacist.</p>

      <p>The <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1159" type="subject"
          >Germans</term> entered <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/460414/daugavpils.html"
          >Dyneburg</placeName> on <date when="1941-06-26">June 26, 1941</date>. On <date
          when="1941-06-29">June 29</date>, they already announced that all <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-826" type="subject">men</term>
        were to be taken. (The Jewish population in <placeName
          ref="http://www.geonames.org/460414/daugavpils.html">Dyneburg</placeName> was from
        10,000-14,000.) Those who were assembled were <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-598" type="subject"
          >arrested</term> and <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-541"
          type="subject">liquidated</term> over the course of 2 weeks. This is how the <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1159" type="subject"
          >Germans</term> began their <q><foreign xml:lang="de">Schreckensherrschaft</foreign></q>.
          <note type="gloss">Schreckensherrschaft (German) – reign of terror</note>. Only <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1427" type="subject"
          >doctors</term> and pharmacists were <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-651" type="subject"
          >released</term>. The rest, about 6,000, were moved on <date when="1941-07-26">July
          26</date> to the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-545"
          type="subject">ghetto</term> outside of town. They lived in former artillery <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-837" type="subject"
          >barracks</term> in stables in terribly <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-295" type="subject">sanitary
          conditions</term>. After a while, Jews were <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-496" type="subject"
          >concentrated</term> there from the entire area. The total number was 7,200. They were
        caught and <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-541" type="subject"
          >shot</term> in groups of 5,000 and 1,000 from the <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-545" type="subject">ghetto</term>.
        The approximately 1,200 who remained were put in <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-669" type="subject">prison</term>.
        On <date when="1941-11-09">November 9, 1941</date>, most of the working <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-819" type="subject"
          >families</term> were taken, who up to that time had been protected, and on <date
          when="1942-05-01">May 1, 1942</date>, the final <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-551" type="subject"
          >liquidation</term> of the <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-545" type="subject">ghetto</term>
        began by means of <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-541"
          type="subject">shooting</term> people on the spot. Those who were <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">working</term>
        for the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1159" type="subject"
          >Germans</term> that day remained alive, about 380-400 people. They <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">worked</term>
        at various <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1159"
          type="subject">German</term> Einheits <note type="gloss">Einheit (German) – unit
          (military)</note> in <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/460414/daugavpils.html"
          >Dyneburg</placeName> until <date when="1943-10">October 1943</date>. I was not faring
        badly. The Jews <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832"
          type="subject">cooked</term> for themselves, received 120 g of <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">bread</term>,
        from time to time <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832"
          type="subject">butter</term>, or <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">sugar</term>,
          <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject"
          >salt</term> etc. In <date when="1943-10">October</date>, they were taken to <placeName
          ref="http://www.geonames.org/456172/riga.html">Riga</placeName> to the electrotechnical
          <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-929" type="subject"
          >factory</term>, [where] parts [were made] for cables, radios, etc. at the <orgName
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-005054">AEG Allgemeine
          Elektrotechnische Genossenschaft</orgName>. They were divided into sections, they <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">worked</term>
        on 3 shifts. Others <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556"
          type="subject">worked</term> for 11 hours from 6 a.m. to 5 p.m. without any breaks (only ½
        hour for <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject"
          >lunch</term>). The <orgName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-429"
          >SS</orgName>
        <foreign xml:lang="de">Oberscharführer</foreign> and <foreign xml:lang="de"
          >Blitzmädel</foreign>
        <note type="gloss">Blitzmädel (German) – „girl with the lighting emblem”, female Wehrmacht
          auxiliary (Wehrmachthelferin), in concentration camps the SS auxiliary
          (SS‑helferin).</note> did not treat them badly. Jewish <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825" type="subject">women</term>
        of all nationalities were concentrated in the <placeName
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-2055" type="camp">Riga
          camp</placeName>, from the <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3077311/czechia.html"
          >Czech lands</placeName>, <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/719819/hungary.html"
          >Hungary</placeName>, <placeName
          ref="http://www.geonames.org/798544/republic-of-poland.html">Poland</placeName>,
          <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/597427/republic-of-lithuania.html"
          >Lithuania</placeName>, <placeName
          ref="http://www.geonames.org/2921044/federal-republic-of-germany.html"
        >Germany</placeName>, etc. Only one <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1159" type="subject">German</term>
        <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825" type="subject"
          >woman</term> was in charge of all of them. They got 250 g of <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-833" type="subject">bread</term>,
        some <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject"
          >marmalade</term> or alternately a piece of <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">fat</term>, a
        little <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject"
          >sugar</term>, <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832"
          type="subject">margarine</term>, <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject"
        >sausage</term>, or <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832"
          type="subject">horse meat</term>. Once a day there was a some <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">soup</term>,
        and <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject"
          >coffee</term> twice a day. The Jewish kitchen stole from them, taking their <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">food</term>
        for their own needs, exchanging it with <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-373" type="subject">Aryans</term>
        for other things, etc. The <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">work</term>
        site was across from their room. The <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-295" type="subject">sanitary
          conditions</term> were very good, warm shower, often <foreign xml:lang="de"
          >Entlausung</foreign>, <note type="gloss">Entlausung - delousing</note> light, warm, in
        their free time they read, played cards. A couple times they had evenings of poetry
        readings, singing in Yiddish. The <q>Blitzerki</q>
        <note type="gloss">„Blitzerki” - Blitzmädel</note> also attended them.</p>
      <p>In <date when="1944-10">October 1944</date>, they were suddenly <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-521" type="subject"
          >transported</term> to <placeName
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-857" type="camp"
          >Stutthof</placeName> (Durchgangslager). <note type="gloss">Stutthof – at present
          Sztutowo. Durchgangslager (German) – transit camp.</note> For a week, they traveled by
        truck in conditions that were lamentable. Near <placeName
          ref="http://www.geonames.org/7531002/gdansk.html">Gdańsk</placeName>, the <orgName
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-350">Gestapos</orgName> beat them
        when they were getting out of the trucks. They were kept at <placeName
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-857" type="camp"
          >Stutthof</placeName> for 1 month. The Jewish <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825" type="subject">women</term>
        from <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/798544/republic-of-poland.html"
          >Poland</placeName> and <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/719819/hungary.html"
          >Hungary</placeName> - <foreign xml:lang="de">Blockälteste</foreign>
        <note type="gloss">Blockälteste – block elder.</note> beat them, and the Jewish <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825" type="subject">women</term>
        from the <foreign xml:lang="de">Innendienst</foreign>
        <note type="gloss">Innendienst – internal service</note> in the blocks beat them as well. In
        the narrow bunk <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-837"
          type="subject">beds</term>, four <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825" type="subject">women</term>
        would sleep together, there was filth everywhere. The harassment got to the point where they
        were not allowed to leave the <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-837" type="subject"
          >barracks</term> to take care of their <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-295" type="subject">physiological
          needs</term>. They were kept for hours at <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-487" type="subject">roll
          calls</term> for no reason. They did not <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">work</term> at
        all. The <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-567" type="subject"
          >camp</term> had a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-501"
          type="subject">crematorium</term> as well. Their <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-833" type="subject">food</term>
        consisted of <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832"
          type="subject">coffee</term> twice a day, one liter of <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-833" type="subject">soup</term>,
        300 g of <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject"
          >bread</term> (some <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832"
          type="subject">margarine</term> or <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject"
          >marmalade</term> occasionally). There were Jews here from all over the world. There were
        also <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-373" type="subject"
          >Aryans</term> there. The whole <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-567" type="subject">camp</term>
        had about 40,000 <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-650"
          type="subject">prisoners</term>. There were 600 people to a <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-486" type="subject"
          >barracks</term>. Leaving the <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-837" type="subject"
          >barracks</term> was forbidden. Contact with the <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-373" type="subject">Aryan</term>
        world was banned.</p>
      <p>After a month, they took 300 people to <placeName
          ref="http://www.geonames.org/7530813/torun.html">Toruń</placeName> to <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">work</term> in
        the electrotechnical <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-929"
          type="subject">factory</term>. There were already about 200 <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-483" type="subject">camp
          inmates</term> there. In <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/7530813/torun.html"
          >Toruń</placeName> they had very bad <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject"
          >conditions</term>. The <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1216" type="subject"
          >Oberscharführer</term> beat them for no reason, they were <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-569" type="subject"
          >starving</term>. A beating with club (25 blows) was an everyday occurrence. People’s hair
        was cut off for the smallest offence. Work in the <orgName
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-005054">AEG</orgName> in
          <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/7530813/torun.html">Toruń</placeName> was
        supervised by <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/458258/republic-of-latvia.html"
          >Latvians</placeName>. They treated Jews very badly. They reported the most minor
        infractions against <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-567"
          type="subject">camp</term>
        <q>law</q> to the Oberscharführer.</p>
      <p><term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-567" type="subject"
          >Camp</term> authorities: <orgName
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-429">SS</orgName>
          Oberscharführer<orgName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-429"
          >SS</orgName> <foreign xml:lang="de">Unterscharführer</foreign> (administrator) normal <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1216" type="subject">SS
          soldiers</term> as <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-480"
          type="subject">camp guards</term></p>
      <p><q><foreign xml:lang="de">Blitzmädel</foreign></q> supervised during <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">work</term> a
        Jewish <foreign xml:lang="de">Lagerältester</foreign>
        <note type="gloss">Lagerältester – camp elder Jewish Blockälteste</note>Jewish "Polizei" -
        2-3 <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825" type="subject"
          >women</term> 12 people were employed in the kitchen.</p>
      <p>The <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-567" type="subject"
          >camp</term> consisted of an enormous square surrounded by barbed wire which was made up
        of 5 blocks, and one that was not yet finished. <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825" type="subject">Women</term>
        lived in 4 <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-837" type="subject"
          >barracks</term>, over 100 to a <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-837" type="subject"
        >barrack</term>. The kitchen and supply room was in the fifth. A <foreign xml:lang="de"
          >Waschraum</foreign>, <note type="gloss">Waschraum - washroom</note> shoemakers’ <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-549" type="subject"
          >workshop</term> and laundry were set up in the sixth. The <q><foreign xml:lang="de"><term
              ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-483" type="subject"
              >Häftlinge</term></foreign></q>
        <note type="gloss">Häftlinge - prisoners</note> wore gray <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-669" type="subject">prison</term>
        <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-836" type="subject"
          >clothing</term> and <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-836"
          type="subject">underwear</term>, numbers that were assigned back in <placeName
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-857" type="camp"
          >Stutthof</placeName>. The <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-837" type="subject"
          >barracks</term> were built of boards, one store high. Triple bunk beds were put in them
        in rows, without any bed linens. One blanket and straw mattress were assigned to 4 <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825" type="subject">women</term>.
        They <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject"
          >worked</term> for 8 hours a day with the cables, and then they shoveled snow and helped
        in the kitchen.</p>
      <p>There were 2 <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556"
          type="subject">work</term> halls. The first was in the <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-567" type="subject">camp</term>,
        the second was in the <q><foreign xml:lang="de">Stadthalle</foreign></q>
        <note type="gloss">Stadthalle – hall in the town</note> in town. People <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">worked</term>
        for 12 hours a day in the second hall. Those who <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">worked</term>
        8 hours a day also had to work on Sundays. Part of the first <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-486" type="subject"
          >barracks</term> was used for the <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-491" type="subject"
          >hospital</term>. The <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-287"
          type="subject">doctor</term> was a Jewish <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825" type="subject">woman</term>.
        The <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1216" type="subject"
          >SS</term> had 3 Jewish cooks for their needs. They treated them better than the others.
        In the morning, they were woken up with a shout of: <q>Aufstehen! <term
            ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-487" type="subject"><foreign
              xml:lang="de">Apell</foreign></term>!</q>
        <note type="gloss">Aufstehen, Apell – stand up, roll call</note> They were counted, and if
        the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1216" type="subject"
          >Oberscharführer</term> was in a good mood, they were sent to <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">work</term>.
        If he was in a bad mood, he kept them for hours in the field. It was the same with those who
        were returning from the <q><foreign xml:lang="de">Nachtschicht</foreign></q>. <note
          type="gloss">Nachtschicht – night shift</note> In the evening, 100 <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825" type="subject">women</term>
        would return from the <q><foreign xml:lang="de">Stadthalle</foreign></q> and 300 from the
          <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-567" type="subject"
          >camp</term>. It was always terribly crowded in the <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-486" type="subject"
          >barracks</term>. At nine, the lights were turned off.</p>
      <p>When the <orgName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-004583"
          >Soviets</orgName> were approaching, the <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1216" type="subject"
          >Oberscharführer</term> assembled them. They were given <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">bread</term>
        for the journey, <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832"
          type="subject">sausage</term> and half a package of <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject"
          >margarine</term> and they left on foot. They <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-517" type="subject">walked</term>
        for 50 kilometers to <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/7530814/bydgoszcz.html"
          >Bromberg</placeName>, <note type="gloss">Bromberg – Bydgoszcz.</note> on the way many
          <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-204" type="subject"
          >escaped</term>, and the <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1216" type="subject"
          >Oberscharführer</term> no longer paid any attention. They <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-517" type="subject">marched</term>
        to <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1159" type="subject"
          >Germany</term> half-dead through the <date when="1945-01">January</date> snows. The <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1159" type="subject"
          >Germans</term> and Blitzerki also <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-204" type="subject">escaped</term>
        on foot. The <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-791"
          type="subject">sick</term> were moved on sleds, which Jews pulled. In <placeName
          ref="http://www.geonames.org/7530814/bydgoszcz.html">Bromberg</placeName>, almost everyone
          <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-204" type="subject">ran
          away</term>, taking advantage of the confusion was prevailing among the <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1159" type="subject"
          >Germans</term>.</p>

      <p><persName ref="#ehri_et_lewin_blanka">Lewinówna</persName> taking the record (<placeName
          ref="http://www.geonames.org/7530970/lublin.html">Lublin</placeName>)</p>
